@NODE "intro"

Looking for a stand-alone, not-very-much hassle FTPd for MorphOS? Then look no further and feast your eyes 
(and your FTPd'ing needs) on OrangeFTPd 1.2, guaranteed to work by me and the one person who tested it for me. 

OrangeFTPd 1.2 is built on the old(er) OrangeFTPd 0.8 (available from an Aminet server near you) and, 
unlike it's predecessor, works with MorphOS. Guide, icons are all from the original archive and updated/downgraded 
(where necessary). 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "license"

It's freeware, so do as you please (unless you intend to use to it harm people/cute animals or for other weird perversions). 
There will be no open sourcing because the code is a crime against humanity and I can't be bothered to clean it up. Or show 
it to anyone for that matter. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "disclaimer"

It might explode. It might catch fire. It might just delete all your files and break your filesystem, it might just work. 
It works for me (tm) :) 

I can't be held responsible for anything bad happening while using this program (so you better lock the door!). 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "install"

OrangeFTPd won't run unless two requirements are met: 

1. The program needs the NList custom classes for MUI. Just download them from Aminet or the dedicated Sourceforge page.
2. You need to have a Group and Users defined (see @{"Usage" LINK "usage"}).

The program itself is standalone, so just copy the main executable where you want it to sit and start the program from there. 
You might want to print the guide and file it in your personal library. You might not. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "usage"

OrangeFTPd is almost completely feature free so making it work comes down to starting the program and, well, eh, that's it really. 
However, to get some use out of it you'll have to take these steps: 


* Go to the MorphOS system preferences and select "Users".

* Select the "Users" tab and add a user (or more users if you have, mhaha,  use for them), add a password, select a user ID 
  (say 1, 2, etc) and select a Group ID (select whatever number, but all the users need to have the same Group ID). The "Home Dir" 
  points to the directory that will be accessed when the user logs in.   
  Oh, and if you add a user called "anonymous", that one won't need a password, because he'll be able to login without one. 

* Select the "Groups" tab, add a group called "ftp" and give the group the same Group ID as the one you selected for the users.  
  Add the names of the users to the "Users" field; seperate the names by spaces.


When you are done configuring your users, simply start OrangeFTPd by either (franticly) clicking the icon or from a shell. 
When run from a shell it won't open the GUI unless you add the "-gui" switch. 

When using the GUI there are some more options available through the "Configuration" button. They're all pretty self-explanatory. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "security"

* General security

Always protect your users with a password and don't ever think FTP is secure :) OrangeFTPd should be free from weird buffer 
overflows exploits. Or at least I hope so ;)

* File security

File permissions are set by the normal AmigaDOS command "protect".
If you don't know how to use protect, here is the short version:

protect file [flags]

Where [flags] should be R, W, D or a combination of those. R for read, W for write and D for delete. Easy :)

New files created inherits the parent directory's permissions.

@ENDNODE

